text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas]]%0a%0a!The Klallam Language%0a%0a:Author: xiranw%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aOn the Lower Elwha Klallam Tribe and their language.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI visited Olympic National Park a few years ago and loved the magnificent landscape. I am interested in learning more about the land, so for this Wiki, I am investigating one of the three tribes who were the original inhabitants of the land--the Lower Elwha Klallam Tribe.%0a%0aLower Elwha refers to the geographical location of the tribe, and Klallam, which is the name of the people, is pronounced /klɑləm/. Historically, multiple spellings of Klallam have been used (Clallam, S’Klallam, etc.), but the official spelling adopted by this tribe is Klallam. In the Point No Point Treaty of 1855, the tribe received federal recognition from the United States and ceded titles to most of their land in exchange for reservations and a small monetary compensation.%0a%0aThe Klallam language is fortunately still alive, with significant revitalization efforts underway. In 1990, there were only eight people who could speak the language. In 1992, in order to preserve the language, the tribe began recording elders speaking the language as a part of the Klallam Language Program. In 1999, Klallam began to be taught at the Port Angeles High School. There is also an indigenous-run YouTube channel posting instructional videos teaching Klallam. Although I was not able to find estimates of how many speakers there are today, the tribe’s website states that “over 200 students have taken two years of Klallam Language” at the high school. Klallam is also beginning to be used ceremonially (e.g., in speeches at community events).%0a%0aInterestingly (and also very surprisingly), the Wikipedia page on the Klallam language claims that the language is extinct, although the tribe’s website makes no such claim and very much portrays the language as undergoing successful revitalization. Wikipedia mentions the teaching of Klallam at the Port Angeles High School, but makes no mention of the Klallam Language Program that is referenced multiple times on the tribe’s website. If I were to write a summary based only on Wikipedia’s information, I would not have been aware of the tribe’s significant revitalization efforts and their praise-worthy successes. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.elwha.org/culture-history/klallam-language/%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/c/KlallamLanguage/featured%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klallam_language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a#foxbegin 210412-221659-287830#%0a(:if1 equal {$:Author} {$Author}:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210412-221659-287830#%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas:)
